# File: specs/feature-per-step-model-effort-config/feature.gherkin
#
# Generated from: specs/feature-per-step-model-effort-config/requirements.md
# Issues: #77, #91

Feature: Per-step model and effort level configuration
  As a developer or SDLC automation agent running the SDLC workflow
  I want per-step model and effort level configuration
  So that each SDLC phase uses the optimal model for its task

  # --- Runner Per-Step Model ---

  Scenario: Per-step model override in runner config
    Given a sdlc-config.json with global model "gpt-5.4"
    And the writeSpecs step has model "gpt-5.5"
    When the runner executes the writeSpecs step
    Then the Codex subprocess is invoked with "--model gpt-5.5"

  Scenario: Global model used as fallback when step has no model override
    Given a sdlc-config.json with global model "gpt-5.4"
    And the startIssue step has no model field
    When the runner executes the startIssue step
    Then the Codex subprocess is invoked with "--model gpt-5.4"

  Scenario: Default model used when neither step nor global specifies model
    Given a sdlc-config.json with no global model field
    And no step has a model field
    When the runner executes any step
    Then the Codex subprocess is invoked with "--model gpt-5.5"

  # --- Runner Per-Step Effort ---

  Scenario: Per-step effort override in runner config
    Given a sdlc-config.json with global effort "high"
    And the startIssue step has effort "medium"
    When the runner executes the startIssue step
    Then the subprocess environment includes model_reasoning_effort set to "medium"

  Scenario: Global effort used as fallback when step has no effort override
    Given a sdlc-config.json with global effort "high"
    And the writeSpecs step has no effort field
    When the runner executes the writeSpecs step
    Then the subprocess environment includes model_reasoning_effort set to "high"

  Scenario: No effort env var set when neither step nor global specifies effort
    Given a sdlc-config.json with no global effort field
    And no step has an effort field
    When the runner executes any step
    Then the subprocess environment does not include model_reasoning_effort

  # --- Implement Step: Single Invocation (AC10, supersedes old plan/code split) ---
  # Added by issue #91

  Scenario: Implement step uses single runCodex invocation
    Given a sdlc-config.json with implement step configured
    When the runner executes the implement step
    Then a single runCodex call is made
    And no runImplementStep function is called
    And the subprocess uses the step-level model and effort configuration

  Scenario: Implement step defaults to gpt-5.5 model and medium effort
    Given a sdlc-config.json with no implement-level model or effort overrides
    And no global model or effort overrides
    When the runner resolves the implement step configuration
    Then the model defaults to "gpt-5.5"
    And the effort defaults to "medium"

  Scenario: Implement step prompt omits EnterPlanMode instruction
    Given the runner builds the prompt for step 4
    When the prompt is constructed
    Then it does not contain "Do NOT call EnterPlanMode"
    And it does not reference EnterPlanMode in any form

  # --- Backward Compatibility ---

  Scenario: Backward compatibility with config lacking per-step overrides
    Given a sdlc-config.json with only global model "gpt-5.5" and no per-step model or effort fields
    When the runner executes the writeSpecs step
    Then the Codex subprocess is invoked with "--model gpt-5.5"
    And the subprocess environment does not include model_reasoning_effort

  # Added by issue #91
  Scenario: Legacy plan/code config is silently ignored
    Given a sdlc-config.json with plan and code sub-objects under steps.implement
    When the runner validates the config
    Then no validation errors are raised for the plan and code sub-objects
    And the step-level implement.model and implement.effort are used for resolution

  # --- Config Template ---

  # Added by issue #91 (supersedes old config template scenario)
  Scenario: Config template shows flat implement config
    Given a user reads sdlc-config.example.json
    When they review the implement step configuration
    Then the implement step has a flat config with model "gpt-5.5" and effort "medium"
    And there are no nested plan or code sub-objects

  # Added by issue #91
  Scenario: Config template shows createPR maxTurns of 30
    Given a user reads sdlc-config.example.json
    When they review the createPR step configuration
    Then maxTurns is 30

  # --- Skill Frontmatter ---

  Scenario: Skill frontmatter includes model field
    Given any nmg-sdlc SKILL.md file
    When Codex loads it for manual invocation
    Then the YAML frontmatter contains a model field
    And the model matches the recommended default for that skill

  Scenario Outline: Each skill has the correct model in frontmatter
    Given the SKILL.md for <skill>
    When the frontmatter is parsed
    Then the model field is <model>

    Examples:
      | skill                    | model  |
      | draft-issue          | gpt-5.4 |
      | open-pr             | gpt-5.4 |
      | init-config | gpt-5.4 |
      | write-code       | gpt-5.5   |
      | migrate-project       | gpt-5.5   |
      | run-retro   | gpt-5.5   |
      | setup-steering      | gpt-5.5   |
      | start-issue          | gpt-5.4 |
      | verify-code          | gpt-5.4 |
      | write-spec            | gpt-5.5   |

  # --- Writing-Specs Auto-Mode Fix ---
  # Added by issue #91

  Scenario: Writing-specs unattended-mode always amends existing spec
    Given unattended-mode is active
    And spec discovery finds a matching existing feature spec
    When the skill decides whether to amend or create
    Then it proceeds directly in amendment mode without calling interactive prompt

  # --- README Documentation ---

  Scenario: README documents model and effort recommendations
    Given a user reads the README
    When they look for model and effort guidance
    Then they find a table of recommended model and effort settings per skill
    And instructions for overriding defaults via runner config

  # --- Config Validation ---

  Scenario: Invalid effort value is rejected at startup
    Given a sdlc-config.json with effort value "maximum"
    When the runner starts
    Then it exits with a non-zero exit code
    And the error message identifies the invalid effort value
    And the error message lists valid options: "low", "medium", "high"

  Scenario: Empty model value is rejected at startup
    Given a sdlc-config.json with model value ""
    When the runner starts
    Then it exits with a non-zero exit code
    And the error message identifies the invalid model value

  # --- Migrating Projects ---

  Scenario: Migration detects new config keys after plugin upgrade
    Given a project with an old-format sdlc-config.json lacking model and effort fields
    When the user runs /migrate-project after upgrading the plugin
    Then the migration proposes adding the missing model and effort keys
    And existing config values are preserved

  # --- Issue #130: Defaults optimization for latest model lineup ---
  # Added by issue #130

  Scenario: validateConfig accepts the xhigh effort tier
    Given a sdlc-config.json with effort value "xhigh" at the global level
    When the runner starts
    Then validateConfig produces no errors for the effort value
    And the runner does not exit due to effort validation

  Scenario: validateConfig accepts xhigh at the per-step level
    Given a sdlc-config.json with the writeSpecs step effort "xhigh"
    When the runner starts
    Then validateConfig produces no errors for steps.writeSpecs.effort
    And the runner does not exit due to effort validation

  Scenario: validateConfig rejects the max effort tier
    Given a sdlc-config.json with effort value "max"
    When the runner starts
    Then validateConfig returns an error identifying effort as invalid
    And the error message states that max is intentionally excluded from nmg-sdlc defaults
    And the runner exits with a non-zero exit code

  Scenario: validateConfig rejects effort on a GPT-5.4 Mini step
    Given a sdlc-config.json with steps.commitPush.model set to "gpt-5.4-mini"
    And steps.commitPush.effort set to "low"
    When the runner starts
    Then validateConfig returns an error identifying steps.commitPush
    And the error message states that GPT-5.4 Mini does not support the effort parameter
    And the runner exits with a non-zero exit code

  Scenario: validateConfig rejects effort on a GPT-5.4 Mini step via global fallback
    Given a sdlc-config.json with global effort "medium"
    And steps.merge.model set to "gpt-5.4-mini"
    And steps.merge has no explicit effort field
    When the runner starts
    Then validateConfig returns an error identifying steps.merge
    And the error message states that GPT-5.4 Mini does not support the effort parameter

  Scenario: Effort tier literal names match OpenAI's spec
    Given a sdlc-config.json with effort value "x-high"
    When the runner starts
    Then validateConfig returns an error identifying the effort value as invalid
    And the error message lists valid options including exactly "xhigh"
    And the error message does not list any hyphenated variants

  Scenario: Runner module default is gpt-5.4/medium
    Given a sdlc-config.json with no global model or effort
    And no per-step model or effort fields
    When resolveStepConfig is called for any step
    Then the returned model is "gpt-5.4"
    And the returned effort is "medium"

  Scenario: Example config pins an explicit model for every step
    Given a user reads scripts/sdlc-config.example.json
    When every step object is inspected
    Then each step declares an explicit model field
    And no step relies on inheritance from the global model

  Scenario: GPT-5.5 is hard-capped to three steps in the example config
    Given a user reads scripts/sdlc-config.example.json
    When every step with model "gpt-5.5" is collected
    Then only writeSpecs, implement, and verify appear in the result
    And startCycle, startIssue, commitPush, createPR, monitorCI, and merge use gpt-5.4 or gpt-5.4-mini

  Scenario Outline: Example config step defaults match the AC30 reference table
    Given a user reads scripts/sdlc-config.example.json
    When the <step> step is inspected
    Then the model is <model>
    And the effort is <effort>
    And maxTurns is <turns>
    And timeoutMin is <time>

    Examples:
      | step        | model  | effort  | turns | time |
      | startCycle  | gpt-5.4-mini  | —       | 10    | 5    |
      | startIssue  | gpt-5.4 | low     | 25    | 5    |
      | writeSpecs  | gpt-5.5   | xhigh   | 60    | 15   |
      | implement   | gpt-5.5   | xhigh   | 150   | 30   |
      | verify      | gpt-5.5   | high    | 100   | 20   |
      | commitPush  | gpt-5.4-mini  | —       | 15    | 5    |
      | createPR    | gpt-5.4 | low     | 45    | 5    |
      | monitorCI   | gpt-5.4 | medium  | 60    | 20   |
      | merge       | gpt-5.4-mini  | —       | 10    | 5    |

  Scenario: GPT-5.4 Mini steps in example config omit the effort field
    Given a user reads scripts/sdlc-config.example.json
    When a step with model "gpt-5.4-mini" is inspected
    Then the effort field is not present on that step object

  Scenario Outline: SDLC runner config declares model matching the runner
    Given the SKILL.md for <skill>
    When the YAML frontmatter is parsed
    Then the model field is <model>

    Examples:
      | skill           | model  |
      | write-spec      | gpt-5.5   |
      | write-code      | gpt-5.5   |
      | verify-code     | gpt-5.5   |
      | start-issue     | gpt-5.4 |
      | open-pr         | gpt-5.4 |
      | draft-issue     | gpt-5.4 |
      | run-retro       | gpt-5.5   |
      | setup-steering  | gpt-5.5   |
      | init-config     | gpt-5.4-mini  |
      | run-loop        | gpt-5.4 |
      | upgrade-project | gpt-5.5   |

  Scenario Outline: Non-GPT-5.4 Mini SDLC skills declare effort matching the runner
    Given the SKILL.md for <skill>
    When the YAML frontmatter is parsed
    Then the effort field is <effort>

    Examples:
      | skill           | effort |
      | write-spec      | xhigh  |
      | write-code      | xhigh  |
      | verify-code     | high   |
      | start-issue     | low    |
      | open-pr         | low    |
      | draft-issue     | medium |
      | run-retro       | high   |
      | setup-steering  | high   |
      | run-loop        | low    |
      | upgrade-project | high   |

  Scenario: init-config SKILL.md omits effort frontmatter
    Given the SKILL.md for init-config
    When the YAML frontmatter is parsed
    Then the model field is "gpt-5.4-mini"
    And the effort field is not present

  Scenario: README documents the precedence chain
    Given a user reads the README Model and Effort Configuration section
    When the precedence subsection is inspected
    Then it lists four layers in order: model_reasoning_effort env var, runner config, session /model or /effort, built-in default
    And the env var is stated to win over runner config
    And the runner config is stated to win over the session override

  Scenario: README documents max exclusion and GPT-5.4 Mini no-effort rules
    Given a user reads the README Model and Effort Configuration section
    When the reader looks for guardrail rules
    Then a note states that max is intentionally excluded from nmg-sdlc defaults
    And a note states that GPT-5.4 Mini does not accept the effort parameter

  Scenario: CHANGELOG Unreleased section records the defaults rework
    Given a user reads CHANGELOG.md
    When the [Unreleased] section is inspected
    Then an entry summarizes the model and effort defaults rework
    And a separate entry summarizes the maxTurns floor bump citing incident #181

  Scenario: upgrade-project surfaces a curated defaults diff (interactive)
    Given an existing sdlc-config.json with prior defaults
    And unattended mode is NOT active
    When /upgrade-project runs
    Then it presents a diff table of each step's model, effort, maxTurns, and timeoutMin changes
    And it offers a batch-approve option for the recommended defaults
    And it offers a per-field review option

  Scenario: upgrade-project reports but does not apply diff in unattended mode
    Given an existing sdlc-config.json with prior defaults
    And unattended mode is active
    When /upgrade-project runs
    Then the recommended defaults diff is recorded in the summary
    And no automatic overwrite of user values occurs
    And the behavior is consistent with the existing value-drift contract

  Scenario: init-config produces a fresh config matching the new defaults
    Given a fresh project with no sdlc-config.json
    When a user runs /nmg-sdlc:init-config
    Then the generated sdlc-config.json matches scripts/sdlc-config.example.json verbatim for per-step defaults
    And no template placeholders remain for model, effort, maxTurns, or timeoutMin
